            "answer_text": "In 1281, a Mongol army set out to invade Japan. The disparity of numbers in the Mongols\u2019 favour was in the order of 4:1. They tried to storm the beaches but couldn\u2019t breach the defensive walls the Japanese had built after an earlier Mongol assault in 1274. The Mongols reorganized and tried again at several other sites but met the same fate. They retreated to their ships to think over their options. As the fleet lay off the coast, a typhoon blasted out of the East and turned most of the ships to matchsticks. Thousands drowned. The survivors packed up and departed in what was left of their ships. They didn\u2019t try again. The Japanese attributed their salvation to divine intervention. They named the phenomenon the \u201cDivine Wind\u201d or Kamikazi. ",
